  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How many Filipino workers were employed in the POGO industry before the 2024 shutdown?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">PAGCOR's final pre-shutdown reporting estimated approximately 32,000 direct Filipino employees in POGO-licensed operations, primarily in customer-facing, language-support, and back-office roles. The total workforce including foreign nationals was estimated at 110,000 to 130,000, though figures vary by source. The Department of Labor and Employment's transition assistance program reached roughly 18,000 of these workers by mid-2025.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Where did displaced Filipino POGO workers go after the shutdown?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">The majority transitioned into the domestic BPO sector, the new PIGO and e-Games licensee workforce, or related digital services. A smaller cohort &mdash; estimated in the low single-digit thousands &mdash; followed operator relocations to Cambodia, Curacao, and other jurisdictions. A further group exited gaming entirely. Precise tracking is limited because no central registry was maintained.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Is it legal for Filipino workers to work for relocated POGO operators in Cambodia?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Working for a Cambodian-licensed gaming operator on a valid work visa is legal under both Philippine and Cambodian law. However, recruitment activities for these positions are tightly regulated under the Philippine Overseas Workers Welfare Administration framework, and many of the relocations occurred through informal recruitment channels that may have violated Philippine labor migration rules.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What are the working conditions in Cambodian online gaming compounds?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Conditions vary dramatically by operator. Larger, professionally managed operations under tier-3 Cambodian licenses operate broadly comparable to the former Manila POGO standard &mdash; long hours, dormitory accommodation, but legal employment terms. Smaller and less-regulated operations, particularly those in border zones or peripheral compounds, have been the subject of repeated UN, US State Department, and Cambodian government concerns regarding labor abuse and trafficking risks.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Why didn't more displaced POGO workers find work in the new PIGO and e-Games sector?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">The PIGO and e-Games sector employs significantly fewer workers per peso of revenue than POGOs did. The domestic-facing model has lower customer support intensity, more automated platforms, and operates at smaller scale than the former offshore industry. Even with the new licensing categories absorbing thousands of former POGO workers, the structural capacity gap meant many had to find work elsewhere.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Is the Philippine government tracking workers who followed operators abroad?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Not systematically. The Department of Migrant Workers (DMW) has bilateral consultations with Cambodia on labor protection, and the Philippine Embassy in Phnom Penh reports informally on welfare cases. But there is no comprehensive registry, and the population of Filipino workers in Cambodian gaming operations is widely believed to be undercounted in official statistics.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

